 a state of indecision, in a misguided attempt to keep their options open. This provisional way of living—always looking elsewhere, to the future, to other people, to other ways of being, and never committing to what one has or, alternatively, putting in the time and energy to achieve what one wants—is a big mistake, and Life Is Short tells readers how to avoid this trap.By reminding us how extraordinary it is that we have any time to live at all, Life Is Short challenges us to rethink what gives life meaning and how to make the most of it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLife. 0aTime management. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aAbsurdity.  aAddiction.  aAdult.  aAlbert Camus.  aAnalytical psychology.  aAscending and Descending.  aBulletproofing.  aCambridge University Press.  aCluster B personality disorders.  aConsciousness.  aCriminal justice.  aCritique.  aDave Asprey.  aDaydream.  aDemiurge.  aDerek Parfit.  aDisease.  aDon Giovanni.  aDon Juanism.  aEleusinian Mysteries.  aEternal return.  aEudaimonia.  aExistence.  aExistentialism.  aGnosticism.  aGrandiosity.  aIdeology.  aImprisonment.  aIn Search of Lost Time.  aIndividuation.  aInstitution.  aJean-Jacques Rousseau.  aJean-Paul Sartre.  aLionel Penrose.  aMartin Heidegger.  aMeaningful life.  aNarcissism.  aNeurosis.  aObstacle.  aOxford University Press.  aPhaedo.  aPhenomenon.  aPhilip Larkin.  aPhilosopher.  aPhilosophy.  aPhysicist.  aPotentiality and actuality.  aPrinceton University Press.  aPrison.  aPrison–industrial complex.  aPsychoanalysis.  aPuer aeternus.  aRacism.  aReality.  aResult.  aRoger Penrose.  aRole.  aSibling.  aSlippery slope.  aStoicism.  aSubjectivity.  aThe Myth of Sisyphus.  aThe Philosopher.  aThe V